Abstract = {Contemporary empiricism has attempted to ground its analysis of science
   in a falsificationism based in selection theory. This paper links these
   evolutionary epistemologies with commitments to certain epistemological
   and ontological assumptions found in the later work of K. Popper, D.
   Campbell, and D. Hull. I argue that their assumptions about the
   character of contemporary empiricism are part of a shared paradigm of
   epistemological explanation which results in unresolved tensions within
   their own projects.  I argue further that their claim to be doing a
   science of science is not defensible. Hull's selectionism is analyzed to
   show how this epistemological agenda has played itself out in late
   empiricism. I suggest some directions that Hull might take toward an
