Abstract = {This paper aims to accelerate scientific discovery by studying link
   prediction in a semantic network. The nodes are unidentified concepts in
   machine learning, and the time-stamped edges indicate co-occurrence in
   scientific papers. Taking advantage of this temporal information, we
   perform node embedding on the graph at every year from 1994 to 2017, and
   apply two methods to find features for node pairs: the first method uses
   a transformer, while the other uses distance metrics combined with known
   link prediction features. The latter feature extraction technique with a
   3-layer multi-layer perceptron achieved an AUC of 0.902 on predicting
   edges in the 2020 graph. Inspection of the resulting features suggests
   that the model does indeed pay attention to the dynamic nature of the
   features, e.g., how node-pair distance in embedding space changes over
   the years.},
