Month = {JUN 22},
Abstract = {Newton's centuries-old wisdom of standing on the shoulders of giants
   raises a crucial yet underexplored question: Out of all the prior works
   cited by a discovery, which one is its giant? Here, we develop a
   discipline-independent method to identify the giant for any individual
   paper, allowing us to better understand the role and characteristics of
   giants in science. We find that across disciplines, about 95\% of papers
   appear to stand on the shoulders of giants, yet the weight of scientific
   progress rests on relatively few shoulders. Defining a new measure of
   giant index, we find that, while papers with high citations are more
   likely to be giants, for papers with the same citations, their giant
   index sharply predicts a paper's future impact and prize-winning
   probabilities. Giants tend to originate from both small and large teams,
   being either highly disruptive or highly developmental. Papers that did
   not have a giant tend to do poorly on average, yet interestingly, if
   such papers later became a giant for other papers, they tend to be
   home-run papers that are highly disruptive to science. Given the crucial
   importance of citation-based measures in science, the developed concept
   of giants may offer a useful dimension in assessing scientific impact
   that goes beyond sheer citation counts.},
